Part 3 — Ash Framework for Phoenix Developers — Relationships part 1

Kamaro Lambert
6 min read
·
Feb 3, 2025

Previously we saw:

  1. How to think in Ash.
  2. How domains, resources and actions work.

In this section we’ll look at how to create, read, update and destroy related data in different relationships types.

By the end of this part, you will know how to work with relationships in the Ash framework. We’ll start with simple examples and move up to more complex examples, as our applications grow.

Insert a Has Many Relationship via manage_relationshp

In our entity relationships, we’ve seen that a category has many articles. So let’s see how to create, read and destroy related data in a has_many relationship type.

Remember that in the relationships block of the Category resource we have defined the following relationship:

# Relationship Block. In this case this resource has many articles
relationships do
  has_many :articles, Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Article do
    description "Relationship with the articles."
    # Tell Ash that the articles table has foreign key column named "category_id"
    destination_attribute :category_id
  end
end

From here we can define an action called create_article of the type update that creates an article under a provided category. To do so go to the Category resource, in the actions section add the following action:

actions do
  default_accept [:name, :slug, :description]
  defaults [:create, :read, :update, :destroy]
  # Add this action
  update :create_article do
    description "Create an article under a specified category"
    # Set atomic to false since this is a 2-steps operation.
    require_atomic? false
    # Specify the parameter that will hold article attributes
    argument :article_attrs, :map, allow_nil?: false
    change manage_relationship(:article_attrs, :articles, type: :create)
  end
end

NB: The article_attrs map must have the same fields as the fields required to create an article.

The manage_relationshp receives 3 parameters. The first is arguments/ attributes, second is the name of the relationship to manage and the 3rd is the options to pass. In our case, we are telling Ash framework to create related article.

Before we can create this article, we need to tell Article resource that it should accept an action of create by going to Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Article and add the following actions blocks:

actions do
  default_accept [:title, :slug, :content, :views_count, :published]
  defaults [:create, :read, :update, :destroy]
End

Let’s now proceed to creating an article under an existing category:

# 1. Get category to create an article under. Assume it exists already
category = Ash.read_first!(Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category)

# 2. Prepare new article data
article_attrs = %{
title: "Getting Started with Zippiker",
slug: "getting-started-zippiker",
content: "Learn how to set up your Zippiker account and configure basic settings.",
views_count: 1452,
published: true
}

# 3 Create an article under this category
category
|> Ash.Changeset.for_update(:create_article, %{article_attrs: article_attrs})
|> Ash.update()

The above codes should return the following results indicating that it was successfully created.

Create Parent and The Child the Same Time

We can also create a category and article at the same time. Here is how to do it:

Go to the Category and in the actions block add the following action

create :create_with_article do
  description "Create a Category and an article under it"
  argument :article_attrs, :map, allow_nil?: false
  change manage_relationship(:article_attrs, :articles, type: :create)
end

Then, create category and its article at the same time like the following

# Define category and related article attributes
attributes = %{
 name: "Features",
 slug: "features",
 description: "Category for features",
 article_attrs: %{
   title: "Compliance Features in Zippiker",
   slug: "compliance-features-zippiker",
   content: "Overview of compliance management features built into Zippiker."
 }
}

# Create category and its article at the same time
Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category
|> Ash.Changeset.for_create(:create_with_article, attributes)
|> Ash.create()

The above command should give you results that looks like the following:

Retrieve Relationships with Ash.Query.load/1

So far, we’ve seen how to insert a has_many into a related resource. Now, let’s learn how to read related data. To retrieve related data, ash uses Ash.Query.load.

Get Kamaro Lambert’s stories in your inbox

Join Medium for free to get updates from this writer.

Assume we already have retrieved a category and stored it in a category variable. We can retrieve related articles like the following:

category_with_articles =
 Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category
 |> Ash.Query.filter(id == ^category.id)


 # Tell Ash to load related articles
 |> Ash.Query.load(:articles)
 |> Ash.read_first!()

Then access category articles like: category_with_articles.articles

Belongs To

Belongs to is the inverse of has_many relationships.

The relationship is defined on the child resource. In our scenario. The Article belongs to the category. So operations happen on the article resource instead of category.

Since we already defined relationships, all we need to do is to add the actions to handle our operations.

The simplest way to start is to add :category_id attribute in the list of accepts so that it can be passed while creating an article. Update the default_accepts to the following

actions do
 default_accept [
   :title,
   :slug,
   :content,
   :views_count,
   :published,
   :category_id # <-- Added for category relationship
 ]


 defaults [:create, :read, :update, :destroy]
end

With the above configuration you can create an article that belongs to a specified category like the following. Assuming that we already have the category retrieved. We can do the following


# Preparate attributes
attributes = %{
 title: "Common Issues During Setup and How to Fix Them",
 slug: "setup-common-issues",
 content: "Troubleshooting guide for common challenges faced.",
 category_id: category.id # Assumes you've retrieved a category from DB
}


# Create article and assign it to an existing category
Article
|> Ash.Changeset.for_create(:create, attributes)
|> Ash.create()

Create Child and Parent at the Same Time

Article is the child while category is the parent. To create the child and the parent at the same time. We’ll need to:

  1. Define the action on the child resource
  2. Prepare attributes inline with the action on the child resource.

Let’s see it in action.

Go to the Article resource(our child) and add the following action in the actions block.

create :create_with_category do
 description "Create an article and its category at the same time"
 argument :category_attrs, :map, allow_nil?: false
 change manage_relationship(:category_attrs, :category, type: :create)
end

With the above action on the Article resource, you can create both the child and the parent at the same time like the following

attributes = %{
 title: "Common Issues During Setup and How to Fix Them",
 slug: "setup-common-issues",
 content: "Troubleshooting guide for common challenges faced.",
 category_attrs: %{
   name: "Troubleshooting",
   slug: "troubleshooting",
   description: "Diagnose and fix identified issues"
 }
}


Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Article
|> Ash.Changeset.for_create(:create_with_category, attributes)
|> Ash.create()

At this point, you should be able to add a has_many relationship for the comments where a comment belongs to the article and article has many comments. To make this happen, head to the article resource and add the following action.

update :add_comment do
 description "Add a comment to an article"
 require_atomic? false
 argument :comment, :map, allow_nil?: false
 change manage_relationship(:comment, :comments, type: :create)
end

Which you’ll call like:

attributes = %{content: "First article content you will see!"}


{:ok, _article} =
  get_article()
 |> Ash.Changeset.for_update(:add_comment, %{comment: attributes})
 |> Ash.update()

Or, add feedback to the article resource via like the following:

update :add_feedback do
 description "Add a feedback to an article"
 require_atomic? false
 argument :feedback, :map, allow_nil?: false
 change manage_relationship(:feedback, :article_feedbacks, type: :create)
end

In the next article we’ll be looking at more other types of relationships.
